It's a story that begins but does not end with a mathematician named Tim Gallas. Gallows is one of the world's most renowned mathematicians. He's a professor at Cambridge University and recipient Off the Fields Medal, often called the noble prize of mathematics. Gallas is also a blogger, and in January of 2009 he used his Blawg to pose a very striking question. Is massively collaborative mathematics possible? So what he was proposing in this post was to use his blawg to attack a difficult, unsolved mathematical problem, a problem which he said he would love to solve completely in the open, using his blawg to post his ideas and his partial progress. What's more, he issued an open invitation, inviting anybody in the world who thought that they had an idea to contribute to post their idea in the comments section off the block. Okay, His hope was that by combining the ideas of many minds, he could make easy work of his hard mathematical problem. He called this experiment the polymath project well, the polymath project got off to a slow start in the 1st 7 hours. Nobody posted any comments, but then a mathematician from the University of British Columbia named Joseph Salome OSI posted a short comment, and this seemed to break the ice because a few minutes later, Ah, high school teacher named Jason Dia posted a suggestion. And a few minutes after that, another mathematician named Terence Tao, also a Fields medalist, posted an idea and things really started to move quickly. At this point, over the next 37 days, 27 different people would post 800 substantive comments containing 170,000 words. I was not a serious participant, but I was following along closely from the start and it was just amazing the speed with which an idea would be tentatively proposed and then really rapidly developed by other people and improved, sometimes discarded. It is just amazing. Gallas described the process as being too ordinary research as driving is to pushing a car. At the end of the 37 days, Gallows used his blood to announce that they had solved the core problem. In fact, they had solved a harder generalization off the problem, the polymath project had succeeded. So what the polymath project suggests, at least to me is that we can use the Internet to build tools that actually expand our ability to solve the most challenging intellectual problems. Well, to put it another way, we can build tools which actively amplify our collective intelligence in much the same way as for millennia. We've used physical tools to amplify how strength. Okay, so what I'd like to talk about today, or what I'd like to explore today is what this means for science. It's much more important than just solving a single mathematical problem. It means an expansion in the range of scientific problems we can hope to attack at all. It means potentially an acceleration in the rate of scientific discovery means a change in the way we construct knowledge itself. So before I get too overexcited, however, I would I would like to talk about some of the challenges some of the problems in particular. I'd like to describe Alia of this approach. So it occurred in 2005 started in 2005 a grad student at Caltech named John Stockton had a very good idea for what he called the quantum wiki or quickie for short. Okay, it's a great idea. What he did with the quickie was three idea of the quickie was that it was going to be a great repositories of human knowledge, much like Wikipedia. But instead of being focused on general knowledge was going to be focused on specialist knowledge in quantum computing. It's gonna be kind of a super textbook for the field. We have information about all the latest research about what the big open problems in the field were. People's speculation about how to solve the problems, and so on, like Wikipedia, the intention waas that it would be written by the users in this case by experts in quantum computing. I was present at the conference at Caltech in 2005 when it was announced, and some of the people who I spoke to were very skeptical. But some of the people were very excited by the idea they were impressed by the implementation. They're impressed by the amount of initial seed material which had been put on the side, and most of all, they were excited by the vision. But just because they're excited didn't mean that they wanted to take the time themselves to contribute. They hoped that other people would do so, and in the end, nobody essentially was really all that interested in contributing. Okay, if you look today, except in a few small corners, the quickie is essentially dead and sad to say, this is quite a common story. Many scientists, in fields ranging from genetics to string theory, have tried to start science. Ricky's along very similar lines, and typically they have failed for essentially the same reason. It's not just signed Twinkies either. Inspired by Facebook, many organizations have tried to create social networks for scientists, which will connect scientists to other people with similar interests. They said they can share things like data or code, their ideas and so on again. It sounds like a good idea, but if you join one of these signs, you'll quickly discover that they're essentially empty, their virtual ghost towns. So what's going on? What's the problem here? Why these promising sites failing? Well, imagine that you're an ambitious young scientist. I know some of you here are ambitious young scientists. Imagine you're an ambitious young scientist. You really would like to get a job, a permanent job, a good job doing the work that you love. But it's incredibly competitive to get such jobs. Often there'll be hundreds of very highly qualified applicants for positions. And so you find yourself working 60 70 80 hours a week, doing the one thing that you know will get you such a job and that is writing scientific papers. You may think that the quickie is a wonderful idea in principle. But you also know that writing a single mediocre paper will be much more for your career and your job prospects in a long series of brilliant contributions to such a sign. So even though you may like the idea, you may think it will advance science more quickly. You find you just can't conceive of it as being part of your job. It's not the only things which can succeed in this kind of environment. Our projects like the polymath project, which even though they employ an unconventional means to an end, they haven't essential conservatism about them. The end product of the polymath project was still a scientific paper. In fact, it was several papers, right, so unconventional means, but conventional in. So there's a kind of conservatism about it. And don't get me wrong. The Plymouth project is terrific, but it is a pity that scientists can only use tools. Lt's which have this kind of conservative nature. So let me tell you a story about an instance where we moved away from this conservatism. It's a rare story with conservatism has been broken occurred in the 19 nineties when, as you know, for the first time, biologists were taking large amounts of genetic data particular in the Human Genome Project. And there were sites online, which would allow biologists to upload that data so it could be shared with other people around the world and analyzed by other people. Probably the best known of these is the site Jen Bank, which some of you may have heard off or used. And these sites, like Jen Bank, had the problem in common with the quickie that scientists they're not paid or rewarded for sharing their data. It's all about a publishing papers, and so there was a considerable reluctance toe actually upload the data. Everybody could see that this was silly, but it was obvious that this was the right thing to do. But just because it was obvious didn't mean that people were actually doing it. And so a meeting was convened in Bermuda in 1996 of many of the world's leading molecular biologists, and they sat and they discussed the problem for several days. And they came up with what are now called the Bermuda Principles, which state that first, once human genetic data is taken in the lab, it should be immediately uploaded to a site like Jen bank. And to that, the data would be in the public domain. And these principles were given teeth because they were taken by the big scientific grand agencies. The U. S. National Institutes of Health, the UK Wellcome Trust actually baked into policy. Okay, so it meant that if you were a scientist he wanted to work on the human genome. You had to agree to abide by these principles. And today I'm very pleased to say, As a result, you can go online, anybody here and download the human genome, so that's a terrific story. But the human genome is just a tiny, tiny fraction of all scientific knowledge, even just in other parts of genetics There's so much knowledge that is still locked up. I spoke with one bio informatization who told me that he'd been quote sitting on the genome off an entire species for more than a year, an entire species. And in other parts of science, it is routine that scientists hoard their data. They hoard the computer code that they write that could be useful potentially to other people. They hoard their best ideas, and they often hold even the descriptions of the problems that they think are most interesting. And so what I and other people in the open science movement would like to do is we'd like to change this situation. We would like to change the culture of science so that scientists become much more strongly motivated to share all of these different kinds of knowledge. We want to change the values of individual scientists so that they start to see it as part of their job, to be sharing their data, to be sharing their code, to be sharing their best ideas and their problems. So, you know, if we can do this, then this kind of change in values, then we will indeed start to see individual scientists rewarded for doing these things. There will be incentives to do them. It's a difficult thing to do. However, you were talking about changing the culture of entire large parts of science. But it has happened before, once in history.
